This example exercises the SecureUDPSocket and friends.

Use ./mkcerts-rsa (or ./mkcerts-dsa) to create certificates for both client and server.
NOTE: If you're running on Windows and don't have localhost in your
hosts file, edit client/bin/client.xml and replace localhost with 127.0.0.1.

To run the server, open a command prompt, navigate to server/bin and type:

Windows:
thekogans_secureudpecho_server-Windows-x86_64-cl-Release-Static.0.1.0.exe -c -l:Debug server.xml

Linux/OS X:
./thekogans_secureudpecho_server-[Linux | OSX]-x86_64-[gcc | clang]-Release-Static.0.1.0 -c -l:Debug server.xml

To run the client, open a command prompt, navigate to client/bin and type:

Windows:
thekogans_secureudpecho_client-Windows-x86_64-cl-Release-Static.0.1.0.exe -l:Debug client.xml

Linux/OS X:
./thekogans_secureudpecho_client-[Linux | OSX]-x86_64-[gcc | clang]-Release-Static.0.1.0 -l:Debug client.xml
